qas.question: What school did Nasser attend in Cairo?
What was the title of the article Nasser wrote for his school paper?
What was the issue Nasser led a protest against?
How many protestors were killed in the demonstration?
What did King Farouk restore after the demonstrations?

context: When his father was transferred to Cairo in 1933, Nasser joined him and attended <a0_0>al-Nahda al-Masria<a0_0/> school. He took up acting in school plays for a brief period and wrote articles for the school's paper, including a piece on French philosopher Voltaire titled "<a1_0>Voltaire, the Man of Freedom<a1_0/>". On 13 November 1935, Nasser led a student demonstration against <a2_0>British rule<a2_0/>, protesting against a statement made four days prior by UK foreign minister Samuel Hoare that rejected prospects for the 1923 Constitution's restoration. <a3_0>Two<a3_0/> protesters were killed and Nasser received a graze to the head from a policeman's bullet. The incident garnered his first mention in the press: the nationalist newspaper Al Gihad reported that Nasser led the protest and was among the wounded. On 12 December, the new king, Farouk, issued a decree restoring the <a4_0>constitution<a4_0/>.
